WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.160
The more people refer to the science,

00:04.240 --> 00:07.120
the more you should suspect that they are engaged

00:07.200 --> 00:10.280
in some quasi-religious activity.

00:10.360 --> 00:14.920
This kind of wrong-headedness leads to all kinds of policy errors

00:15.000 --> 00:19.200
because people have focused on the satisfaction of asceticism.

00:19.280 --> 00:22.240
It's very significant that in our lifetimes,

00:22.320 --> 00:26.120
governments have got worse at dealing with disasters, not better.

00:26.200 --> 00:28.520
Despite the accumulation of scientific knowledge,

00:28.640 --> 00:32.960
we seem somehow, collectively, to be worse at scientific thinking.

00:47.560 --> 00:50.080
Hello, everyone, watching and listening.

00:50.160 --> 00:53.280
Today, I'm speaking with historian and author Neil Ferguson.

00:53.360 --> 00:56.760
We haven't spoken before, although I've wanted to for a long time.

00:56.920 --> 01:01.120
We discuss the historical and deeply mythological precedent

01:01.200 --> 01:03.640
of world-ending narratives,

01:03.720 --> 01:06.520
how the Global Doomsday Ethos

01:06.600 --> 01:11.400
abdicates local responsibility while empowering the elite class,

01:11.480 --> 01:16.600
the out-of-control gigantism plaguing our administrative states today,

01:16.680 --> 01:19.240
and how we might strive as individuals

01:19.320 --> 01:22.320
to deal with the genuine tragedy of life,

01:22.400 --> 01:26.040
morally, humbly, and religiously.

01:26.160 --> 01:30.520
So, I was reviewing your book, Doom, this morning,

01:30.600 --> 01:33.440
and I've been wanting to talk to you about it for a long time.

01:33.520 --> 01:38.640
I'm very interested in the apocalyptic vision

01:38.720 --> 01:46.760
and its implications for political organization

01:46.840 --> 01:49.840
and psychological organization as well.

01:49.920 --> 01:53.840
And I thought I'd just start with a couple of comments to get us going.

01:54.840 --> 01:57.720
The apocalypse, in some ways, is always upon us,

01:57.800 --> 02:00.400
and you write about that in your book.

02:00.480 --> 02:02.520
I mean, because people might ask,

02:02.600 --> 02:09.880
well, why has mankind always been consumed at the narrative level

02:09.960 --> 02:11.720
with notions of the end of the world?

02:11.800 --> 02:14.520
And the answer to that is at least in part

02:14.600 --> 02:20.840
because we always inhabit demarcated conceptual worlds

02:20.920 --> 02:22.120
and even embodied worlds,

02:22.120 --> 02:25.000
and all of those worlds do come to an end.

02:25.080 --> 02:28.080
And so, the idea that there's a universal end

02:28.160 --> 02:30.480
is built into the fabric of reality,

02:30.560 --> 02:33.880
and it's something that we have to permanently contend with.

02:33.960 --> 02:38.360
And so, it's there as a lurking existential abyss,

02:38.440 --> 02:41.600
but it's also there as a practical problem that we have to contend with.

02:41.680 --> 02:46.920
And the grand apocalyptic visions, the book of Revelation, for example,

02:47.000 --> 02:50.360
are in part attempts to structure our apprehension

02:50.600 --> 02:55.320
of the, what would you say, the eternal apocalypse

02:55.400 --> 02:59.280
and to also help us determine, practically and politically,

02:59.360 --> 03:03.200
how that might be at least staved off,

03:03.280 --> 03:07.560
although perhaps even managed more comprehensively.

03:07.640 --> 03:10.840
And so, I guess I'm curious,

03:10.920 --> 03:13.280
why did your interest, do you think,

03:13.360 --> 03:15.480
coalesce around the conception of doom?

03:15.560 --> 03:20.320
And it's been a couple of years now since this book was published,

03:20.400 --> 03:23.080
how have your conceptions changed?

03:23.160 --> 03:30.080
And what did you learn as a consequence of investigating this narrative trope so deeply?

03:30.160 --> 03:35.520
There's a great sketch in the Beyond the Fringe album,

03:35.600 --> 03:40.600
which goes right back to Peter Cook and Dudley Moore,

03:40.680 --> 03:44.840
Jonathan Miller and Alan Bennett in the 1960s.

03:44.920 --> 03:46.920
And the sketch is the end of the world,

03:47.160 --> 03:51.800
and it's essentially a sect of millenarians who gather on a hill

03:51.880 --> 03:55.120
to anticipate the end of the world.

03:55.200 --> 03:59.720
They have a long and quite amusing discussion about what it's likely to involve.

03:59.800 --> 04:03.280
Will the veil of the temple be rent asunder?

04:03.360 --> 04:07.960
And the time comes, they count down to the end of the world,

04:08.040 --> 04:09.440
and nothing happens.

04:09.520 --> 04:11.840
And Peter Cook, who's the leader of the sect,

04:11.920 --> 04:16.760
ends the sketch by, well, never mind, lads, same time next week.

04:16.760 --> 04:19.720
And I always thought that was very funny,

04:19.800 --> 04:24.120
because the end of the world has been consistently overpredicted

04:24.200 --> 04:27.880
by human beings for millennia.

04:27.960 --> 04:30.360
We're fascinated by the idea of the end of the world,

04:30.440 --> 04:32.760
and I think it's for a slightly different reason

04:32.840 --> 04:35.680
from the one that you hypothesized.

04:35.760 --> 04:42.480
We have the reality that we as individuals end to contend with.

04:42.600 --> 04:48.720
That's just one of the givens of human life.

04:48.800 --> 04:51.760
Even for billionaires in Silicon Valley,

04:51.840 --> 04:57.880
right now, the end of their individual lives is inevitable.

04:57.960 --> 05:03.400
And that's really the hardest thing to deal with about life, that it ends.

05:03.480 --> 05:06.760
And we also know how it ends, we know what that's like,

05:06.840 --> 05:11.000
because at some time or another in our lives, we encounter death.

05:11.080 --> 05:14.480
The death of a grandparent, a parent, of a friend.

05:14.560 --> 05:17.560
We also see things being destroyed.

05:17.640 --> 05:21.600
We see buildings collapse or bridges.

05:21.680 --> 05:24.920
We see fires consume areas of woodland.

05:25.000 --> 05:27.040
So we know what dissolution looks like,

05:27.120 --> 05:28.640
not just for us as individuals,

05:28.720 --> 05:34.120
but we know what it looks like for expanses of land or edifices.

05:34.200 --> 05:38.360
And I think we therefore infer the consoling thought

05:38.480 --> 05:44.320
that it's all going to go down in flames at some future date.

05:44.400 --> 05:46.520
And the great monotheistic religions

05:46.600 --> 05:49.800
have as one of their centerpieces the end of the world.

05:49.880 --> 05:53.520
It's there in Islam as well as in Christianity.

05:54.600 --> 05:56.000
And I think it's also exciting.

05:56.080 --> 06:01.440
I think we find the end of the world kind of a cinematic prospect,

06:01.520 --> 06:04.000
which is why there are so many movies about it,

06:04.080 --> 06:06.320
as well as works of science fiction.

06:06.360 --> 06:08.440
So we're fascinated by the end of the world

06:08.520 --> 06:11.040
because it's clearly a spectacular prospect,

06:11.120 --> 06:14.160
but it's also consoling to us, we may die as individuals,

06:14.240 --> 06:16.640
but everything's going down at some point.

06:16.720 --> 06:18.400
And the issue is when?

06:18.480 --> 06:25.320
So many Christians at successive periods in the history of Christianity

06:25.400 --> 06:28.960
have anticipated quite an imminent end of the world.

06:29.040 --> 06:31.120
And of course, they're always disappointed,

06:31.200 --> 06:33.240
like Peter Cook and Dudley Moore.

06:33.320 --> 06:35.760
So the consoling issue,

06:35.800 --> 06:37.800
I mean, the easy read on that, I suppose,

06:37.880 --> 06:41.320
is that the end of the world is the precondition

06:41.400 --> 06:44.760
for the establishment of an ever more glorious paradise.

06:44.840 --> 06:47.760
And you can understand a consolation in that.

06:47.840 --> 06:51.320
But you're pointing to a different kind of consolation, I suppose,

06:51.400 --> 06:54.120
which is, it seems to me, correct me if I'm wrong,

06:54.200 --> 06:58.160
that something like Schadenfreude is that the fact that we end

06:58.240 --> 07:01.320
is easier to swallow if we understand it

07:01.400 --> 07:04.360
in relationship to the potential end of everything.

07:04.400 --> 07:08.520
So I don't exactly understand why you highlighted consolation.

07:08.600 --> 07:12.360
I can see it in the heavenly vision, let's say, post-apocalypse,

07:12.440 --> 07:15.360
but yours, you seem to be pointing to something else.

07:15.440 --> 07:20.600
Well, of course, religion offers an afterlife

07:20.680 --> 07:25.960
that will be better and resurrection in the case of

07:26.040 --> 07:29.040
the great monotheistic religions.

07:29.120 --> 07:33.160
But I don't think that's always what's in people's minds

07:33.240 --> 07:35.760
when they contemplate the end of the world.

07:35.840 --> 07:37.720
I was very struck as I was researching the book,

07:37.800 --> 07:41.960
how many times in the midst of a localized disaster,

07:42.040 --> 07:46.000
individuals said it felt like the end of the world.

07:46.080 --> 07:51.680
So when you're in the midst of a massive conflagration,

07:51.760 --> 07:54.760
the biggest wildfire in US history,

07:54.840 --> 07:59.040
or when you're in London during the Blitz,

07:59.120 --> 08:03.040
when you're in the midst of some localized disaster,

08:03.320 --> 08:05.240
it seems somehow consoling to say,

08:05.320 --> 08:07.960
oh, it's clearly the end of the world.

08:08.040 --> 08:10.080
So I don't think it's just that people say,

08:10.160 --> 08:14.360
and therefore I can look forward to being reunited with my ancestors

08:14.440 --> 08:16.200
in some happy afterlife.

08:16.280 --> 08:18.920
I think there's just a sense that if everybody's going down,

08:19.000 --> 08:21.800
that doesn't make it quite so bad as if it's just me.

08:22.680 --> 08:25.720
Well, you know, there might be another element to it as well.

08:25.800 --> 08:29.920
I mean, the Terminator movie series came to mind

08:29.920 --> 08:33.760
when you were walking through your discussion,

08:33.840 --> 08:36.040
I suppose, in reference to the science fiction

08:36.120 --> 08:37.680
representations of the end of the world.

08:37.760 --> 08:42.560
And all of our conceptual schemes,

08:42.640 --> 08:44.760
when they encounter an obstacle,

08:44.840 --> 08:47.160
undergo a collapse into a kind of chaos

08:47.240 --> 08:48.840
and then a potential regeneration.

08:48.920 --> 08:51.600
And that's the same as a stage transition

08:51.680 --> 08:54.080
in Piagetian child development.

08:54.160 --> 08:56.280
And it's the same as the scientific revolution.

08:56.320 --> 09:00.320
And every act of learning is simultaneously

09:00.400 --> 09:03.040
the death of some set of preconceptions.

09:03.120 --> 09:04.960
And there's pain in that,

09:05.040 --> 09:07.680
which is partly why we don't like to have our ideas challenged.

09:07.760 --> 09:09.520
But you know, there's also adventure in it.

09:09.600 --> 09:13.520
And part of the reason that people do go to watch movies

09:13.600 --> 09:18.320
like The Terminator and the plethora of the end of the world

09:18.400 --> 09:20.680
movies that do make themselves manifest

09:20.760 --> 09:24.920
is because I think we can see in the confrontation

09:24.960 --> 09:28.240
with cataclysm an adventure.

09:28.320 --> 09:29.920
I mean, that's what people are doing in a theater

09:30.000 --> 09:31.680
when they're watching the Terminator series.

09:31.760 --> 09:33.440
I mean, it's a dreadful adventure,

09:33.520 --> 09:34.840
but it's a total adventure.

09:34.920 --> 09:36.240
It's completely engrossing.

09:36.320 --> 09:39.560
And it might be that you could imagine,

09:39.640 --> 09:42.280
and I think that this is part of the emphasis

09:42.360 --> 09:45.640
of the Judeo-Christian notion of ultimate sacrifice.

09:45.720 --> 09:50.440
