you have the construction of monstrous state-like apparatuses

37:27.040 --> 37:33.920
aligned with individual fragmentation down to the point of licentious atomization.

37:34.000 --> 37:35.920
That's a good way of thinking about it.

37:36.000 --> 37:40.320
So you're striving towards, it seems to me in your argument,

37:40.400 --> 37:42.560
you're striving towards the hypothesis

37:42.560 --> 37:46.640
that there's something like an out-of-control gigantism

37:46.720 --> 37:55.040
that's causally related to the inability of these bureaucratic organizations

37:55.120 --> 37:58.880
to actually respond to actual occurrences in the world.

37:58.960 --> 38:01.040
So two thoughts.

38:01.120 --> 38:02.400
There's only one law of history.

38:02.480 --> 38:07.280
I'm a historian, and that's the law of unintended consequences.

38:07.360 --> 38:11.600
And so what typically happens is that well-intentioned people

38:11.760 --> 38:16.400
come to power, identify a problem which they feel they must address,

38:16.480 --> 38:19.680
and they undertake measures to address the problem

38:19.760 --> 38:21.520
which have unintended consequences.

38:21.600 --> 38:24.560
This was true when back in the 1960s and 70s,

38:24.640 --> 38:27.840
people persuaded themselves that there was a terrible problem of overpopulation

38:27.920 --> 38:29.920
that Malthus was going to be vindicated,

38:30.000 --> 38:33.440
and therefore there had to be drastic population control, especially in Asia.

38:33.520 --> 38:37.120
And that turned out to have all kinds of unintended consequences.

38:37.120 --> 38:42.800
In our time, fears not just of climate change,

38:42.880 --> 38:48.480
but of dangerous technological developments have given rise

38:48.560 --> 38:53.040
to a view which my friend Nick Bostrom and Oxford exemplifies,

38:53.120 --> 38:56.880
that we need to have very, very powerful surveillance powers

38:56.960 --> 38:59.920
to prevent bad things from happening,

39:00.000 --> 39:03.200
whether it's to prevent CO2 emissions

39:03.280 --> 39:08.800
in reaching the levels of the net zero program,

39:08.880 --> 39:11.520
or whether it's to stop dangerous research

39:11.600 --> 39:13.760
being done with artificial intelligence,

39:13.840 --> 39:18.320
we need to empower the state to have even greater powers of surveillance

39:18.400 --> 39:21.440
than the mid-20th century totalitarian regimes had.

39:21.520 --> 39:24.320
And so one of the key arguments in the book DOOM is that

39:24.400 --> 39:29.040
actually totalitarianism is the thing most to be feared.

39:29.120 --> 39:33.600
In the 20th century, totalitarian regimes caused way more premature death

39:33.680 --> 39:35.120
than anything else.

39:35.200 --> 39:38.000
And so the last thing we should want to do in the 21st century

39:38.080 --> 39:40.800
is to create new forms of totalitarianism

39:40.880 --> 39:46.160
out of the belief that only an all-seeing state can prevent disaster.

39:46.240 --> 39:49.520
So this is a really, really important argument that the book makes,

39:49.600 --> 39:52.880
and I think it's become even more relevant with the major breakthroughs

39:52.960 --> 39:58.720
we've seen in artificial intelligence in the two years since the book was published.

39:58.720 --> 40:04.160
The other thing that I would say is we want the universe to be moral.

40:04.240 --> 40:08.240
We are very strongly inclined to think when bad things happen to us

40:08.320 --> 40:14.000
that they may in fact be retribution for sins that we committed in the past.

40:14.080 --> 40:20.720
And even the most rational individual is susceptible to this idea.

40:20.800 --> 40:25.520
I know this because my parents did their very best to raise me

40:25.600 --> 40:30.960
as a product of the Scottish Enlightenment, an atheist and a devoted believer

40:31.040 --> 40:32.320
in the scientific method.

40:32.400 --> 40:35.440
But when bad things happen, I have this uneasy sense

40:35.520 --> 40:39.840
that I may have brought it upon myself by transgressing in some way,

40:39.920 --> 40:43.680
illustrating that you can't really escape the Christian legacy

40:43.760 --> 40:50.000
unless you travel a very long, long way away from post-Christian civilizations.

40:50.080 --> 40:52.400
Now, it's not, in fact, a moral universe.

40:52.480 --> 40:54.480
This is the bad news.

40:54.560 --> 40:55.280
It's really not.

40:55.360 --> 40:59.040
I mean, a lot of the bad things that happen are random.

40:59.120 --> 41:01.440
They're governed by power laws.

41:01.520 --> 41:03.600
They're extremely difficult to predict.

41:03.680 --> 41:07.200
Wars are, in fact, pretty randomly distributed.

41:07.280 --> 41:10.960
There's no cycle of history that tells you when a war is coming.

41:11.040 --> 41:13.440
Same applies to financial crises.

41:13.520 --> 41:17.200
Wildfires and earthquakes are not normally distributed.

41:17.280 --> 41:20.560
They can't really be thought of in probabilistic terms.

41:20.640 --> 41:23.440
And so much of the terrible stuff that happens to us

41:23.520 --> 41:28.240
has nothing to do with there being a moral universe.

41:28.320 --> 41:32.800
A cancer may strike one of us down in a much shorter timeframe

41:32.880 --> 41:36.000
than we're both tacitly assuming we have.

41:36.080 --> 41:40.960
And if we are diagnosed with a terminal cancer,

41:41.040 --> 41:42.640
how will we react to that news?

41:42.720 --> 41:44.960
What if I hear this tomorrow?

41:45.040 --> 41:47.520
It'll be a tremendous shock to me,

41:47.520 --> 41:52.240
mainly because it will render my younger children

41:52.320 --> 41:54.720
much more vulnerable in my absence.

41:54.800 --> 41:56.640
But will I be able to resist the temptation

41:56.720 --> 41:58.080
that I brought it upon myself?

41:58.160 --> 42:00.720
It'll be there in the back of my mind

42:00.800 --> 42:06.000
because I've just inherited from generations that way of thinking.

42:06.080 --> 42:10.400
And it's worth adding one little footnote to this.

42:10.480 --> 42:12.320
My friend, the historian Tom Holland,

42:12.400 --> 42:16.080
wrote a nice book recently, Dominion, arguing that

42:16.160 --> 42:18.320
Christian ways of thinking about the world

42:18.400 --> 42:24.400
have outlived Christianity in these secular times that we inhabit.

42:24.480 --> 42:26.720
A very good illustration of this point

42:26.800 --> 42:30.240
is how much Calvinism is still out there.

42:30.320 --> 42:33.520
The belief that you belong to the elect,

42:33.600 --> 42:35.440
the people because of predestination

42:35.520 --> 42:39.600
who are insured of salvation, is a very powerful one.

42:39.680 --> 42:42.960
And it persists long after people have ceased to attend

42:43.040 --> 42:45.440
