46:42.000 --> 46:45.840
is that she encounters the serpent who turns out to be Satan.

46:45.920 --> 46:50.480
So it's the possibility of predation

46:50.560 --> 46:54.400
and natural catastrophe allied with the possibility of evil.

46:54.480 --> 46:56.720
That's a good way of thinking about it symbolically.

46:56.800 --> 47:00.160
And her first presumption

47:00.160 --> 47:05.040
is that she can encompass that and hearken to it

47:05.120 --> 47:08.480
and listen to its voice and integrate it.

47:08.560 --> 47:10.880
And that's what produces the fall.

47:10.960 --> 47:14.240
And Adam's Consequent Sin, as he agrees with Eve,

47:14.320 --> 47:17.280
and I would say mostly to try to impress her,

47:17.360 --> 47:19.760
which speaks very deeply to the motivation of men.

47:19.840 --> 47:23.680
And so there's this notion, it's a very, very interesting notion.

47:23.760 --> 47:25.280
And I'd like to know what you make of it,

47:25.280 --> 47:30.640
is that the fundamental reason that cataclysms occur,

47:30.720 --> 47:35.920
and I guess this is an objection to your theory of an amoral world.

47:36.000 --> 47:37.920
So we'll see where this goes,

47:38.000 --> 47:40.720
is that it's people's overreaching pride

47:40.800 --> 47:43.680
that is the eternal precursor to the fall.

47:43.760 --> 47:45.440
You know, pride goes before a fall.

47:45.520 --> 47:49.360
But it's this notion that we can fight off more than we can chew,

47:49.440 --> 47:54.880
that we can encapsulate and control more than we're really competent to.

47:54.880 --> 47:59.280
We have an over-expansive vision of our competence.

47:59.360 --> 48:03.360
We trumpet that to parade our moral virtue.

48:03.440 --> 48:08.640
It motivates us to overextend ourselves in places we shouldn't.

48:08.720 --> 48:14.240
And the constant consequence of that is systemic collapse

48:14.320 --> 48:15.600
at different scales.

48:15.680 --> 48:18.400
And so it begs the question, you know, I've really wondered about this,

48:18.480 --> 48:25.440
and you know, if you, I think it's something to meditate on,

48:25.520 --> 48:28.640
if you didn't overreach in your life,

48:28.720 --> 48:34.960
you know, if you were properly humble in your claims of mastery,

48:35.040 --> 48:38.080
if you only dealt with what was local

48:38.160 --> 48:40.160
and that was within your bounds of competence,

48:40.240 --> 48:43.760
you know, maybe extending yourself a bit to learn,

48:43.840 --> 48:47.280
maybe you wouldn't bring on yourself a continual sequence

48:47.280 --> 48:49.920
of relatively apocalyptic catastrophes, right?

48:50.000 --> 48:52.560
It's like, and you pointed to that at the end

48:52.640 --> 48:54.000
of your last sequence of comments.

48:54.080 --> 48:56.720
You know, you said, there's a tension there.

48:56.800 --> 48:59.440
You said, well, the universe is full of random events

48:59.520 --> 49:01.520
and it's not essentially moral.

49:01.600 --> 49:05.680
But you also said, but we overreach constantly

49:05.760 --> 49:09.360
and that does produce, you know, various forms of cataclysm.

49:09.440 --> 49:13.440
So I would say, see, there's a paradox in those two viewpoints

49:13.440 --> 49:15.360
because how about this?

49:15.440 --> 49:18.720
Is how about our immorality makes us more susceptible

49:18.800 --> 49:22.240
to the random fluctuations of the world, right?

49:22.320 --> 49:24.960
That joins those two visions together.

49:25.040 --> 49:29.920
I think it's rather different from the way you've put it.

49:30.000 --> 49:37.120
It's often people with a strong sense of morality who overreach.

49:37.200 --> 49:38.800
Humility is important.

49:38.880 --> 49:40.720
We need to be humble about our ability

49:40.800 --> 49:42.880
to predict the consequences of our actions.

49:42.960 --> 49:47.520
It's a nonlinear world, but we are quite linear thinkers

49:47.600 --> 49:50.560
and we love to say other things being equal,

49:50.640 --> 49:54.400
this act will have the following consequence.

49:54.480 --> 49:59.120
But of course, other things are not equal in a complex system.

49:59.200 --> 50:02.080
Let me give you an illustration of this point,

50:02.160 --> 50:04.720
which is currently in people's minds

50:04.800 --> 50:08.960
because of the success of the movie Oppenheimer.

50:09.040 --> 50:12.560
Oppie Oppenheimer was a very moral individual,

50:12.640 --> 50:17.840
at least he felt himself to be rooted in an ethical education

50:17.920 --> 50:20.960
that he'd had at an elite school in New York,

50:21.040 --> 50:30.800
drawn out of those ethical premises towards communism in the 1930s.

50:30.880 --> 50:35.440
But when given the challenge to build an atomic bomb

50:35.520 --> 50:39.120
in order to win World War II,

50:39.200 --> 50:44.720
he embraced that challenge and achieved it with astonishing brilliance,

50:44.800 --> 50:49.120
brilliance both as a scientist and as it turned out as a leader of scientists.

50:49.200 --> 50:53.920
But he quickly began to see, after the bomb had been dropped

50:54.000 --> 50:59.120
on Hiroshima and Nagasaki, that there were unintended consequences.

50:59.200 --> 51:01.680
He was unable to prevent the arms race

51:01.680 --> 51:05.360
that soon broke out between the United States and the Soviet Union.

51:05.440 --> 51:10.960
He was unable to prevent the invention of the thermonuclear bomb, the super.

51:11.040 --> 51:16.640
He lost the arguments about the development of nuclear weapons.

51:16.720 --> 51:18.960
And if one looks back at that era,

51:19.040 --> 51:24.160
the single most amazing thing to me about that breakthrough

51:24.240 --> 51:28.160
is that we have subsequently made so much more use

51:28.240 --> 51:31.840
of the destructive potential of nuclear fission

51:31.920 --> 51:34.400
than of its productive potential.

51:34.480 --> 51:40.000
We've built many, many more nuclear warheads than nuclear reactors.

51:40.080 --> 51:43.440
That illustrates, I think, very powerfully the law of unintended consequences.

51:43.520 --> 51:48.080
But it began with an individual, Oppenheimer,

51:48.160 --> 51:51.280
who was filled with a sense of his own morality

51:51.360 --> 51:54.800
and took that sense with him to the grave.

51:54.880 --> 51:57.360
Right, okay, but maybe that, okay,

51:57.440 --> 51:59.520
but you're pointing to something there

51:59.600 --> 52:01.600
that is akin to a point you made earlier,

52:01.680 --> 52:06.480
is that you said that he was filled with a sense of his own morality.

52:06.560 --> 52:10.880
And I can understand why that might be associated

52:10.960 --> 52:13.680
with the totalitarian temptation

52:13.760 --> 52:17.120
of religious dogmatism and Calvinism, let's say.

52:17.200 --> 52:20.480
But I could say, perhaps I could say in response,

52:20.560 --> 52:22.160
he should have been filled instead

52:22.240 --> 52:26.160
with a sense of his own potential sinfulness, right?

52:26.240 --> 52:27.360
And I would also say that,

52:27.440 --> 52:28.880
and you can tell me what you think about this,

52:28.960 --> 52:31.600
because these are ideas that I'm just trying to develop,

52:31.680 --> 52:35.360
is that you already told me that as far as you're concerned,

52:35.440 --> 52:38.800
it's the very people who regard themselves as the elect and the saved

52:38.880 --> 52:42.640
and the already moral who are most likely to overreach

52:42.720 --> 52:44.480
and who present the biggest danger.

52:44.560 --> 52:47.040
You followed that up with a description of Oppenheimer, right?

52:47.120 --> 52:50.560
This incredible Luciferian intellect,

52:50.560 --> 52:54.000
and that's the proper symbolic representation

52:54.080 --> 52:57.760
who engaged in this world-destroying scheme

52:57.840 --> 52:59.920
and then was potentially world-destroying scheme

53:00.000 --> 53:01.840
and was unable to control it.

53:01.920 --> 53:05.840
But you characterized him as convinced of his own moral virtue.

53:05.920 --> 53:08.080
So I would say, okay, well, if that's the problem,

53:08.160 --> 53:11.840
maybe he should have been convinced of the opposite of that,

53:11.920 --> 53:15.680
which would be his intrinsic insufficiency and sinfulness.

53:15.760 --> 53:19.360
Now, there is a continual injunction throughout the biblical corpus

53:19.440 --> 53:20.800
to do precisely that.

53:20.880 --> 53:22.880
And the reason I'm bringing that up, too,

53:22.960 --> 53:26.800
is because something else that you said begs a question, you know?

53:26.880 --> 53:31.600
If the law of unintended consequence rules,

53:31.680 --> 53:37.200
then under what conditions is action, any action, not overreach, right?

53:37.280 --> 53:40.240
Because you could say, this is combinatorial explosion,

53:40.320 --> 53:46.080
you can't predict the consequence of any action, and yet you have to act.

53:46.160 --> 53:48.640
And so then the question emerges,

53:48.640 --> 53:50.800
well, since you have to act,

53:50.880 --> 53:55.440
but there's the danger of exponentially cascading unintended consequences,

53:55.520 --> 53:58.080
in what spirit should you act?

53:58.160 --> 54:01.040
And you've already pointed out, well, it shouldn't be in the spirit

54:01.120 --> 54:07.600
of smug, self-satisfied, Calvinistic, dogmatic certainty in your moral right.

54:07.680 --> 54:08.800
Well, then what should it be?

54:08.880 --> 54:11.360
Well, hopefully it should be the opposite of that.

54:11.440 --> 54:14.400
You know, and that is a kind of radical humility, right?

54:14.480 --> 54:17.200
It's an openness to the possibility of error.

54:17.200 --> 54:20.000
I mean, I don't know exactly how those things should be calibrated,

54:20.080 --> 54:22.720
but because we do have to act,

54:22.800 --> 54:25.120
and it does seem to me that there is a domain of action.

54:25.200 --> 54:30.560
Like, what do you think it was that Oppenheimer did wrong, fundamentally?

54:30.640 --> 54:34.080
I mean, I characterize his intellect as Luciferian, right?

54:34.160 --> 54:40.880
He's reaching for a power that, in principle,

54:40.960 --> 54:43.440
I don't know if it should have been forever off limits.

54:43.520 --> 54:45.520
I have no idea how to adjudicate that.

54:45.520 --> 54:50.640
But you have a sense that Oppenheimer himself recognized that he had,

54:50.720 --> 54:54.400
it wasn't that he had too much faith in the comprehensiveness of his intellect,

54:54.480 --> 54:57.120
that he was too tempted by the power that was offered to him

54:57.200 --> 55:01.280
as a consequence of being developer of this immense weapon.

55:01.360 --> 55:03.440
Where do you think he went wrong?

55:03.520 --> 55:06.720
That's key to the question of where science itself goes wrong.

55:06.800 --> 55:09.360
I should be, I haven't watched the movie,

55:09.440 --> 55:12.000
but I read the book American Prometheus.

55:12.080 --> 55:14.800
I prefer books to movies.

55:14.960 --> 55:19.280
And the book makes it clear that what Oppenheimer got wrong

55:19.360 --> 55:22.800
was to flirt with communism.

55:22.880 --> 55:28.320
And that was wrong because it was the moment when he set aside

55:28.400 --> 55:33.840
his scientific judgment and drank at least some of the snake oil

55:33.920 --> 55:38.320
that the Soviet regime was successfully exporting in the 1930s.

55:38.400 --> 55:41.920
This was a terrible mistake that ultimately undermined his credibility

55:42.000 --> 55:48.480
and limited his power to steer the course of the nuclear race.

55:48.560 --> 55:52.400
What he got right was to develop a bomb that could end World War II

55:52.480 --> 55:55.600
without the need for a large-scale conventional forces invasion of Japan

55:55.680 --> 56:01.520
which would have cost untold numbers of American soldiers' lives.

56:01.600 --> 56:04.000
And I think it's very important to emphasize

56:04.080 --> 56:07.280
that if Oppenheimer had said to himself,

56:07.360 --> 56:15.040
I must be humble and resist the temptation to win this race.

56:15.120 --> 56:18.640
And of course, a number of physicists did take that view

56:18.720 --> 56:21.040
and refused to participate in the Manhattan Project.

56:21.120 --> 56:22.880
It might have been disastrous.

56:22.960 --> 56:28.320
I constantly try to remind people in the work I've done on the Second World War

56:28.400 --> 56:32.640
that the Axis powers, the Totalitarian powers, nearly won that war.

56:32.720 --> 56:36.320
And it took tremendous creativity by a whole range of scientists,

56:36.320 --> 56:40.320
not only Oppenheimer, but think of touring those cryptographers

56:40.400 --> 56:45.600
who did such a crucial job of making sure that the Allied powers cracked

56:45.680 --> 56:47.360
or the Axis powers codes.

56:47.440 --> 56:52.560
It took a huge effort to win that war.

56:52.640 --> 56:59.840
The critical thing, I think, comes from another secular Jewish intellect,

56:59.920 --> 57:04.480
Henry Kissinger, whose biography I've spent a large part of my career writing.

57:04.720 --> 57:10.000
In the 1950s and 60s, Kissinger, before he entered the realm of power,

57:10.080 --> 57:13.280
came up with the idea of the problem of conjecture.

57:13.360 --> 57:15.440
It's an extremely important idea

57:15.520 --> 57:17.840
that should be communicated to any decision maker,

57:17.920 --> 57:20.640
whether they're in the private sector or the public sector.

57:20.720 --> 57:23.920
And the problem of conjecture says that at any given moment

57:24.000 --> 57:29.200
when one must take a decision, there is a kind of asymmetry.

57:29.280 --> 57:33.760
And the asymmetry arises from the fact that if you act,

57:33.840 --> 57:41.680
let's say if you had acted in 1938 to prevent Hitler's takeover of Czechoslovakia,

57:41.760 --> 57:43.280
there would have been a cost.

57:43.360 --> 57:45.920
The war would have begun earlier.

57:46.000 --> 57:50.880
And even if you had successfully prevented a much larger war,

57:50.960 --> 57:53.120
the World War that broke out in 1939,

57:53.200 --> 57:55.760
you would have got no real gratitude for that.

57:55.840 --> 57:59.520
You get no payoffs for the averted catastrophe.

57:59.600 --> 58:02.080
Your preemptive action has a cost,

58:02.160 --> 58:04.640
and that you're held responsible for.

58:04.720 --> 58:07.200
The tempting thing, particularly in a democratic system,

58:07.280 --> 58:11.520
is to do nothing, hope for the best, because that has a low cost.

58:11.600 --> 58:16.000
And if disaster nevertheless happens, if you're unlucky,

58:16.080 --> 58:17.360
then you say to yourself,

58:17.440 --> 58:20.960
well, anybody in my position would have made the same error.

58:21.040 --> 58:23.600
So the cost of preemption is high,

58:23.680 --> 58:26.400
and you have to take a decision conjecturally.

58:26.480 --> 58:30.160
Because you can't know that in acting in 1938,

58:30.240 --> 58:33.040
you avert a much larger and more dangerous war.

58:33.120 --> 58:34.640
You cannot have that certainty,

58:34.720 --> 58:36.640
and there are no data that will tell you.

58:36.720 --> 58:39.280
So I think decision-making under uncertainty

58:39.360 --> 58:43.520
is the hardest thing of all, but it has to be done.

58:43.600 --> 58:46.720
And I think what I've learned from Kissinger is that

58:46.800 --> 58:51.760
you will be held responsible and judged very harshly

58:51.840 --> 58:54.240
for those actions you take.

58:54.320 --> 58:56.800
Even if they avert disaster, you won't get thanked.

58:56.880 --> 59:00.160
Nobody ever will thank Henry Kissinger for avoiding World War III.

59:02.240 --> 59:05.280
Nobody will, I think, ever thank any statesman

59:05.360 --> 59:07.040
for avoiding calamity.

59:07.120 --> 59:10.240
They will only blame them for the actions that they took.

59:10.320 --> 59:12.640
And here's the final point that Kissinger makes.

59:12.720 --> 59:16.720
Most choices in the realm of power are between evils.

59:16.800 --> 59:18.880
You just have to decide which is the greater

59:18.960 --> 59:20.320
and which is the lesser.

59:20.400 --> 59:23.120
There are very frequently no good options.

59:23.200 --> 59:25.680
I think that's very clear today in the Middle East

59:25.760 --> 59:30.880
since we're talking at a time of fresh disaster in that region.

59:30.960 --> 59:34.720
There are no good choices facing the Israeli government

59:34.800 --> 59:37.120
or even the government of the United States.

59:37.200 --> 59:39.520
But there's no option to do nothing.

59:39.600 --> 59:40.960
I think that must be clear.

59:41.840 --> 59:43.840
Let me take apart what you just said.

59:43.920 --> 59:51.920
And so the first thing you brought up is that Oppenheimer flirted with,

59:52.720 --> 59:55.680
let's call it, radical left utopianism.

59:56.400 --> 01:00:00.880
Now, that's very interesting because I would say that's true

01:00:00.960 --> 01:00:04.480
of intellectuals across the West and has been since the...

01:00:05.360 --> 01:00:06.800
What? I don't know.

01:00:06.880 --> 01:00:10.720
The last 100 years, and it's certainly something

01:00:10.800 --> 01:00:14.720
that characterizes the academia at the moment.

01:00:14.800 --> 01:00:17.520
I mean, Larry Summers came out two days ago,

01:00:17.600 --> 01:00:21.360
the former president of Harvard, savaging Harvard

01:00:21.360 --> 01:00:25.520
as a consequence of its descent into this radical leftist,

01:00:25.600 --> 01:00:27.120
statist utopian vision.

01:00:27.200 --> 01:00:34.240
So there's something key to the presumption of the intellect

01:00:34.320 --> 01:00:37.600
and belief in a state-imposed utopia.

01:00:37.680 --> 01:00:38.960
So that's one thing.

01:00:39.040 --> 01:00:42.880
Then you said sequence of things that were very, very complicated.

01:00:43.440 --> 01:00:49.680
The first was, well, inaction also produces a combinatorial explosion.

01:00:49.680 --> 01:00:52.240
So we're stuck with the necessity of action.

01:00:52.320 --> 01:00:53.440
So that's a big problem.

01:00:53.520 --> 01:00:56.560
That brings up the issue again, is then under what conditions

01:00:56.640 --> 01:00:57.840
is action appropriate?

01:00:58.640 --> 01:01:06.000
Then you said you're also not rewarded for preventative action

01:01:06.080 --> 01:01:09.360
because in part because nobody can tell what you prevented

01:01:09.440 --> 01:01:10.640
if it doesn't happen, right?

01:01:10.720 --> 01:01:13.600
And so there's no public virtue in that.

01:01:13.680 --> 01:01:17.680
And that entices the leaders of modern states

01:01:17.680 --> 01:01:21.680
to forestall action because they'll be blamed for action

01:01:21.760 --> 01:01:25.120
and then maybe to react precipitously once it's too late.

01:01:25.680 --> 01:01:29.200
So then again, we're back to the central question here,

01:01:29.280 --> 01:01:36.880
at least in part, which is how do you organize your attention

01:01:36.960 --> 01:01:42.560
and sequence your action so that overreach is least likely?

01:01:42.640 --> 01:01:45.440
Now, you discussed Kissinger in that regard

01:01:45.520 --> 01:01:49.520
and said that he was constantly choosing between evils

01:01:49.600 --> 01:01:52.400
and regarded that as a necessity of statescraft.

01:01:53.840 --> 01:01:55.280
You have to conduct yourself.

01:01:56.880 --> 01:02:00.240
We talked earlier about this idea that there's a tremendous

01:02:00.880 --> 01:02:06.320
moral hazard in praying in public and signaling virtue to yourself

01:02:06.400 --> 01:02:09.840
and demanding recognition for your positive actions.

01:02:09.840 --> 01:02:16.480
And you said that prevention doesn't produce public claim.

01:02:17.840 --> 01:02:20.000
That what that has to mean, at least in part,

01:02:20.080 --> 01:02:22.320
is that you have to be oriented to act properly

01:02:22.400 --> 01:02:27.520
despite its reputational advantage or cost, right?

01:02:27.600 --> 01:02:30.880
See, that's exactly it, is that something other than reputation

01:02:30.960 --> 01:02:32.560
has to motivate your action.

01:02:32.640 --> 01:02:36.800
And then the question is, what should motivate your action

01:02:36.800 --> 01:02:40.800
if it's not status, power, and reputation, right?

01:02:40.880 --> 01:02:42.560
That's exactly right. That's where that should...

01:02:42.640 --> 01:02:47.040
Inoch Powell said all political careers end in failure.

01:02:48.160 --> 01:02:53.520
I think that any leader should reconcile himself or herself

01:02:54.080 --> 01:02:58.400
to ultimate failure because doing the right thing,

01:02:58.480 --> 01:03:02.000
averting disaster, will not get you rewarded.

01:03:02.960 --> 01:03:04.720
And I think this is just to...

01:03:04.720 --> 01:03:07.280
So then why bother? Why bother doing the right thing?

01:03:07.360 --> 01:03:09.840
And how do you even determine what the right thing is

01:03:09.920 --> 01:03:13.200
if it's not associated with public acclaim?

01:03:13.280 --> 01:03:14.400
What would right be?

01:03:14.480 --> 01:03:18.480
Because it must have ultimately been right for Churchill

01:03:18.560 --> 01:03:22.720
to speak out against appeasement, as he did throughout the 1930s,

01:03:22.800 --> 01:03:26.960
to take the helm in 1940 when all his predictions had been fulfilled

01:03:27.040 --> 01:03:30.240
and Britain had been brought to the brink of catastrophe,

01:03:30.320 --> 01:03:34.240
to lead Britain to an ultimate victory in 1945,

01:03:34.240 --> 01:03:37.680
and then suffer a massive electoral defeat.

01:03:37.760 --> 01:03:39.360
This is a noble story.

01:03:40.000 --> 01:03:44.320
And I think that's what any leader should aspire to,

01:03:44.400 --> 01:03:47.040
to be right on the basis of historical judgment,

01:03:47.120 --> 01:03:52.080
to accept that there will not necessarily be triumphal processions,

01:03:52.160 --> 01:03:55.440
that there may, in fact, be ignominy at the end of the road,

01:03:55.520 --> 01:03:58.800
but to have done the right thing, to save your nation

01:03:58.880 --> 01:04:01.680
and get no thanks for it, that seems to be the most

01:04:01.760 --> 01:04:03.920
that any leader can aspire to.

01:04:04.000 --> 01:04:05.200
Okay, okay, okay.

